Class ConceptComparator

  • java.lang.Object
    • at.tugraz.kmi.medokyservice.fca.lib.colibri.lib.ConceptComparator
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Comparator<Concept>

     class ConceptComparator
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Comparator<Concept>
    A comparator that imposes a total ordering on concepts.

    The ordering imposed by this comparator is consistent with equals, i.e. compare(c1, c2) returns 0 if and only if c1.equals(c2) returns true, provided that the c1 and c2 belong to the same concept lattice.

    Version:
    1.0
    Author:

      • ConceptComparator

        ConceptComparator(ConceptOrder order,
                 int factor)
            throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Constructs a concept comparator that compares the concepts according to the specified order. The result of the comparation will then be multiplied by the factor provided.

        If factor is negative the comparation will be inverted. For example, if order is ConceptOrder.OBJ_SIZEFIRST and factor is positive, a concept that containing more objects is regarded as greater then a concept with fewer objects by this comparator. If factor is negative, a concept containing more objects will be regarded as smaller then a concept with fewer objects by this comparator.

        Parameters:
        order - the order by which the concepts will be compared.
        factor - the factor by which the result of the comparation will be multiplied.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if factor == 0

    • Method Detail

      • compare

        public int compare(Concept o1,
          Concept o2)
        Compares the two argument concepts for order. Returns a negative integer if the first concept is smaller than the second, a positive integer if the first argument is greater than the second and zero if both concepts are equal. Whether a concept is regarded to be smaller or larger than the other one is determined by the arguments passed to the constructor.
        Specified by:
        compare in interface java.util.Comparator<Concept>
        Parameters:
        o1 - the first concept to be compared.
        o2 - the second concept to be compared.
        Returns:
        a negative integer, zero, or a positive integer as the first concept is less, equal, or greater than the second one.
